                <note rend="inline" type="source">124.52/135: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Third Secretary of Embassy in Spain</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wendelin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Madrid</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-11-07T18:00:00+00:00"
                            >November 7, 1936—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 7—8:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>X–284. This morning Embassy was informed that guards would be relieved and other
                    Embassies were similarly advised. Since permanent <pb facs="0853" n="754"
                        xml:id="pg_754"/> assignment of present guards at the Embassy has been point
                    upon which I have insisted from the beginning as essential measure of
                    protection, receiving repeated assurances thereon from Minister of State, I
                    managed to see Alvarez del Vayo at War Ministry this afternoon and through his
                    intercession Minister of Gobernacion agreed to countermand order insofar as this
                    Embassy is concerned. No actual attempt to relieve guards has been made.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wendelin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
